enums.name: UpgradeMode

values.name: automatic
values.doc: All virtual machines in the scale set are automatically updated at the same time.

values.name: manual
values.doc: You control the application of updates to virtual machines in the scale set. You do this by using the manualUpgrade action.

values.name: rolling
values.doc: The existing instances in a scale set are brought down in batches to be upgraded. Once the upgraded batch is complete, the instances will begin taking traffic again and the next batch will begin. This continues until all instances brought up-to-date.

enums.doc:
Specifies the mode of an upgrade to virtual machines in the scale set.

Possible values are:

**Manual** - You control the application of updates to virtual machines in the scale set. You do this by using the manualUpgrade action.

**Automatic** - All virtual machines in the scale set are automatically updated at the same time.

**Rolling** - Scale set performs updates in batches with an optional pause time in between.

none - The caching mode for the disk is not enabled.
readOnly - The caching mode for the disk is read only.
readWrite - The caching mode for the disk is read and write.

properties.name: policy
properties.summary: The placement policy for allocating nodes in the pool.
properties.doc: Allocation policy used by Batch Service to provision the nodes. If not specified, Batch will use the regional policy.

properties.name: extensions
properties.summary: The virtual machine extension for the pool.
properties.doc: If specified, the extensions mentioned in this configuration will be installed on each node.

valueType.name: BatchVmExtension
valueType.doc: The configuration for virtual machine extensions.

properties.name: name
properties.doc: The name of the virtual machine extension.

properties.name: publisher
properties.doc: The name of the extension handler publisher.

properties.name: ExtensionType
properties.doc: The type of the extensions.

properties.name: typeHandlerVersion
properties.doc: The version of script handler.

properties.name: autoUpgradeMinorVersion
properties.doc: Indicates whether the extension should use a newer minor version if one is available at deployment time. Once deployed, however, the extension will not upgrade minor versions unless redeployed, even with this property set to true.

properties.name: enableAutomaticUpgrade
properties.doc: Indicates whether the extension should be automatically upgraded by the platform if there is a newer version of the extension available.

properties.name: settings
properties.doc: JSON formatted public settings for the extension.

properties.name: protectedSettings
properties.doc: The extension can contain either protectedSettings or protectedSettingsFromKeyVault or no protected settings at all.

properties.name: provisionAfterExtensions
properties.summary: The collection of extension names.
properties.doc: Collection of extension names after which this extension needs to be provisioned.

properties.name: OSDisk
properties.summary: Settings for the operating system disk of the Virtual Machine.
properties.doc: Contains configuration for ephemeral OSDisk settings.

type.name: BatchOSDisk
type.doc: Settings for the operating system disk of the virtual machine.

properties.name: ephemeralOSDiskSettings
properties.doc: Specifies the ephemeral Disk Settings for the operating system disk used by the virtual machine.

type.name: DiffDiskSettings
type.doc: Specifies the ephemeral Disk Settings for the operating system disk used by the virtual machine.

properties.name: placement
properties.summary: Specifies the ephemeral disk placement for operating system disk for all VMs in the pool.
properties.doc: This property can be used by user in the request to choose which location the operating system should be in. e.g., cache disk space for Ephemeral OS disk provisioning. For more information on Ephemeral OS disk size requirements, please refer to Ephemeral OS disk size requirements for Windows VMs at https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/virtual-machines/windows/ephemeral-os-disks#size-requirements and Linux VMs at https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/virtual-machines/linux/ephemeral-os-disks#size-requirements.

properties.name: caching
properties.doc: The type of caching to enable for the disk.

properties.name: managedDisk
properties.summary: The managed disk parameters.

properties.name: storageAccountType
properties.doc: The storage account type for use in creating data disks or OS disk.

properties.name: securityProfile
properties.summary: Specifies the security profile for the managed disk.
properties.doc: Specifies the security profile settings for the managed disk. **Note**: It can only be set for Confidential VMs and is required when using Confidential VMs.

type.name: VMDiskSecurityProfile
type.doc: Specifies the security profile settings for the managed disk. **Note**: It can only be set for Confidential VMs and is required when using Confidential VMs.

properties.name: securityEncryptionType
properties.doc: Specifies the EncryptionType of the managed disk. It is set to VMGuestStateOnly for encryption of just the VMGuestState blob, and NonPersistedTPM for not persisting firmware state in the VMGuestState blob. **Note**: It can be set for only Confidential VMs and required when using Confidential VMs.

properties.name: diskSizeGB
properties.doc: The initial disk size in GB when creating new OS disk.

properties.name: IsWriteAcceleratorEnabled
properties.doc: Specifies whether writeAccelerator should be enabled or disabled on the disk.

properties.name: securityProfile
properties.doc: Specifies the security profile settings for the virtual machine or virtual machine scale set.

type.name: BatchSecurityProfile
type.doc: Specifies the security profile settings for the virtual machine or virtual machine scale set.

properties.name: securityType
properties.doc: Specifies the SecurityType of the virtual machine. It has to be set to any specified value to enable UefiSettings.

properties.name: encryptionAtHost
properties.doc: This property can be used by user in the request to enable or disable the Host Encryption for the virtual machine or virtual machine scale set. This will enable the encryption for all the disks including Resource/Temp disk at host itself.

properties.name: uefiSettings
properties.doc: Specifies the security settings like secure boot and vTPM used while creating the virtual machine.

type.name: BatchUefiSettings
type.doc: Specifies the security settings like secure boot and vTPM used while creating the virtual machine.

properties.name: IsSecureBootEnabled
properties.doc: Specifies whether secure boot should be enabled on the virtual machine.

properties.name: IsVTpmEnabled
properties.doc: Specifies whether vTPM should be enabled on the virtual machine.

properties.name: serviceArtifactReference
properties.summary: Specifies the service artifact reference id used to set same image version for all virtual machines in the scale set when using 'latest' image version.
properties.doc: The service artifact reference id in the form of /subscriptions/{subscriptionId}/resourceGroups/{resourceGroup}/providers/Microsoft.Compute/galleries/{galleryName}/serviceArtifacts/{serviceArtifactName}/vmArtifactsProfiles/{vmArtifactsProfilesName}

type.name: ServiceArtifactReference
type.doc: Specifies the service artifact reference id used to set same image version for all virtual machines in the scale set when using 'latest' image version.

properties.name: id
properties.summary: The service artifact reference id of ServiceArtifactReference
properties.doc: The service artifact reference id in the form of /subscriptions/{subscriptionId}/resourceGroups/{resourceGroup}/providers/Microsoft.Compute/galleries/{galleryName}/serviceArtifacts/{serviceArtifactName}/vmArtifactsProfiles/{vmArtifactsProfilesName}

properties.name: currentDedicatedNodes
properties.doc: The number of dedicated compute nodes currently in the pool.

properties.name: currentLowPriorityNodes
properties.doc: The number of Spot/low-priority compute nodes currently in the pool.

properties.name: scaleSettings
properties.summary: Settings which configure the number of nodes in the pool.
properties.doc: Defines the desired size of the pool. This can either be 'fixedScale' where the requested targetDedicatedNodes is specified, or 'autoScale' which defines a formula which is periodically reevaluated. If this property is not specified, the pool will have a fixed scale with 0 targetDedicatedNodes.

type.name: BatchAccountPoolScaleSettings
type.doc: Defines the desired size of the pool. This can either be 'fixedScale' where the requested targetDedicatedNodes is specified, or 'autoScale' which defines a formula which is periodically reevaluated. If this property is not specified, the pool will have a fixed scale with 0 targetDedicatedNodes.

properties.name: fixedScale
properties.summary: Fixed scale settings for the pool.
properties.doc: This property and autoScale are mutually exclusive and one of the properties must be specified.

type.name: BatchAccountFixedScaleSettings
type.doc: Fixed scale settings for the pool.

properties.name: resizeTimeout
properties.summary: The timeout for allocation of compute nodes to the pool.
properties.doc: The default value is 15 minutes. Timeout values use ISO 8601 format. For example, use PT10M for 10 minutes. The minimum value is 5 minutes. If you specify a value less than 5 minutes, the Batch service rejects the request with an error; if you are calling the REST API directly, the HTTP status code is 400 (Bad Request).

properties.name: targetDedicatedNodes
properties.summary: The desired number of dedicated compute nodes in the pool.
properties.doc: At least one of targetDedicatedNodes, targetLowPriorityNodes must be set.

properties.name: targetLowPriorityNodes
properties.summary: The desired number of Spot/low-priority compute nodes in the pool.
properties.doc: At least one of targetDedicatedNodes, targetLowPriorityNodes must be set.

properties.name: nodeDeallocationOption
properties.summary: Determines what to do with a node and its running task(s) if the pool size is decreasing.
properties.doc: If omitted, the default value is Requeue.

properties.name: autoScale
properties.summary: AutoScale settings for the pool.
properties.doc: This property and fixedScale are mutually exclusive and one of the properties must be specified.

type.name: BatchAccountAutoScaleSettings
type.doc: AutoScale settings for the pool.

properties.name: formula
properties.doc: A formula for the desired number of compute nodes in the pool.

properties.name: evaluationInterval
properties.summary: The time interval at which to automatically adjust the pool size according to the autoscale formula.
properties.doc: If omitted, the default value is 15 minutes (PT15M).

properties.name: autoScaleRun
properties.summary: The results and errors from the last execution of the autoscale formula.
properties.doc: This property is set only if the pool automatically scales, i.e. autoScaleSettings are used.

type.name: BatchAccountPoolAutoScaleRun
type.doc: The results and errors from an execution of a pool autoscale formula.

properties.name: evaluationTime
properties.doc: The time at which the autoscale formula was last evaluated.

properties.name: results
properties.summary: The final values of all variables used in the evaluation of the autoscale formula.
properties.doc: Each variable value is returned in the form $variable=value, and variables are separated by semicolons.

properties.name: error
properties.summary: Details of the error encountered evaluating the autoscale formula on the pool, if the evaluation was unsuccessful.
properties.doc: An error that occurred when autoscaling a pool.

type.name: AutoScaleRunError
type.doc: An error that occurred when autoscaling a pool.

properties.name: code
properties.doc: An identifier for the error. Codes are invariant and are intended to be consumed programmatically.

properties.name: message
properties.doc: A message describing the error, intended to be suitable for display in a user interface.

properties.name: details
properties.doc: Additional details about the error.

properties.name: interNodeCommunication
properties.summary: Whether the pool permits direct communication between nodes.
properties.doc: This imposes restrictions on which nodes can be assigned to the pool. Enabling this value can reduce the chance of the requested number of nodes to be allocated in the pool. If not specified, this value defaults to 'Disabled'.

properties.name: networkConfiguration
properties.summary: The network configuration for the pool.
properties.doc: The network configuration for a pool.

type.name: BatchNetworkConfiguration
type.doc: The network configuration for a pool.

properties.name: subnetId
properties.summary: The ARM resource identifier of the virtual network subnet which the compute nodes of the pool will join. This is of the form /subscriptions/{subscription}/resourceGroups/{group}/providers/{provider}/virtualNetworks/{network}/subnets/{subnet}.
properties.doc: The virtual network must be in the same region and subscription as the Azure Batch account. The specified subnet should have enough free IP addresses to accommodate the number of nodes in the pool. If the subnet doesn't have enough free IP addresses, the pool will partially allocate compute nodes and a resize error will occur. The 'MicrosoftAzureBatch' service principal must have the 'Classic Virtual Machine Contributor' Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) role for the specified VNet. The specified subnet must allow communication from the Azure Batch service to be able to schedule tasks on the compute nodes. This can be verified by checking if the specified VNet has any associated Network Security Groups (NSG). If communication to the compute nodes in the specified subnet is denied by an NSG, then the Batch service will set the state of the compute nodes to unusable. If the specified VNet has any associated Network Security Groups (NSG), then a few reserved system ports must be enabled for inbound communicationincluding ports 29876 and 29877. Also enable outbound connections to Azure Storage on port 443. For more details see: https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/batch/batch-api-basics#virtual-network-vnet-and-firewall-configuration

properties.name: dynamicVNetAssignmentScope
properties.doc: The scope of dynamic vnet assignment.

properties.name: endpointConfiguration
properties.summary: The configuration for endpoints on compute nodes in the Batch pool.
properties.doc: The endpoint configuration for a pool.

type.name: PoolEndpointConfiguration
type.doc: The endpoint configuration for a pool.

properties.name: inboundNatPools
properties.summary: A list of inbound NAT pools that can be used to address specific ports on an individual compute node externally.
properties.doc: The maximum number of inbound NAT pools per Batch pool is 5. If the maximum number of inbound NAT pools is exceeded the request fails with HTTP status code 400. This cannot be specified if the IPAddressProvisioningType is NoPublicIPAddresses.

valueType.name: BatchInboundNatPool
valueType.doc: A inbound NAT pool that can be used to address specific ports on compute nodes in a Batch pool externally.

properties.name: name
properties.summary: The name of the endpoint.
properties.doc: The name must be unique within a Batch pool, can contain letters, numbers, underscores, periods, and hyphens. Names must start with a letter or number, must end with a letter, number, or underscore, and cannot exceed 77 characters.  If any invalid values are provided the request fails with HTTP status code 400.

properties.name: protocol
properties.doc: The protocol of the endpoint.

properties.name: backendPort
properties.summary: The port number on the compute node.
properties.doc: This must be unique within a Batch pool. Acceptable values are between 1 and 65535 except for 29876 and 29877 as these are reserved. If any reserved values are provided the request fails with HTTP status code 400.

properties.name: frontendPortRangeStart
properties.summary: The first port number in the range of external ports that will be used to provide inbound access to the backendPort on individual compute nodes.
properties.doc: Acceptable values range between 1 and 65534 except ports from 50000 to 55000 which are reserved. All ranges within a pool must be distinct and cannot overlap. If any reserved or overlapping values are provided the request fails with HTTP status code 400.

properties.name: frontendPortRangeEnd
properties.summary: The last port number in the range of external ports that will be used to provide inbound access to the backendPort on individual compute nodes.
properties.doc: Acceptable values range between 1 and 65534 except ports from 50000 to 55000 which are reserved by the Batch service. All ranges within a pool must be distinct and cannot overlap. If any reserved or overlapping values are provided the request fails with HTTP status code 400.

properties.name: networkSecurityGroupRules
properties.summary: A list of network security group rules that will be applied to the endpoint.
properties.doc: The maximum number of rules that can be specified across all the endpoints on a Batch pool is 25. If no network security group rules are specified, a default rule will be created to allow inbound access to the specified backendPort. If the maximum number of network security group rules is exceeded the request fails with HTTP status code 400.

valueType.name: BatchNetworkSecurityGroupRule
valueType.doc: A network security group rule to apply to an inbound endpoint.

properties.name: priority
properties.summary: The priority for this rule.
properties.doc: Priorities within a pool must be unique and are evaluated in order of priority. The lower the number the higher the priority. For example, rules could be specified with order numbers of 150, 250, and 350. The rule with the order number of 150 takes precedence over the rule that has an order of 250. Allowed priorities are 150 to 4096. If any reserved or duplicate values are provided the request fails with HTTP status code 400.

properties.name: access
properties.doc: The action that should be taken for a specified IP address, subnet range or tag.

properties.name: sourceAddressPrefix
properties.summary: The source address prefix or tag to match for the rule.
properties.doc: Valid values are a single IP address (i.e. 10.10.10.10), IP subnet (i.e. 192.168.1.0/24), default tag, or * (for all addresses).  If any other values are provided the request fails with HTTP status code 400.

properties.name: sourcePortRanges
properties.summary: The source port ranges to match for the rule.
properties.doc: Valid values are '*' (for all ports 0 - 65535) or arrays of ports or port ranges (i.e. 100-200). The ports should in the range of 0 to 65535 and the port ranges or ports can't overlap. If any other values are provided the request fails with HTTP status code 400. Default value will be *.

properties.name: publicIPAddressConfiguration
properties.summary: The Public IPAddress configuration for Compute Nodes in the Batch Pool.
properties.doc: The public IP Address configuration of the networking configuration of a Pool.

type.name: BatchPublicIPAddressConfiguration
type.doc: The public IP Address configuration of the networking configuration of a Pool.

properties.name: provision
properties.summary: The provisioning type for Public IP Addresses for the Batch Pool.
properties.doc: The default value is BatchManaged

properties.name: IPAddressIds
properties.summary: The list of public IPs which the Batch service will use when provisioning Compute Nodes.
properties.doc: The number of IPs specified here limits the maximum size of the Pool - 100 dedicated nodes or 100 Spot/low-priority nodes can be allocated for each public IP. For example, a pool needing 250 dedicated VMs would need at least 3 public IPs specified. Each element of this collection is of the form: /subscriptions/{subscription}/resourceGroups/{group}/providers/Microsoft.Network/publicIPAddresses/{ip}.

properties.name: enableAcceleratedNetworking
properties.summary: Whether this pool should enable accelerated networking.
properties.doc: Accelerated networking enables single root I/O virtualization (SR-IOV) to a VM, which may lead to improved networking performance. For more details, see: https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/virtual-network/accelerated-networking-overview.

properties.name: taskSlotsPerNode
properties.summary: The number of task slots that can be used to run concurrent tasks on a single compute node in the pool.
properties.doc: The default value is 1. The maximum value is the smaller of 4 times the number of cores of the vmSize of the pool or 256.

properties.name: taskSchedulingPolicy
properties.summary: How tasks are distributed across compute nodes in a pool.
properties.doc: If not specified, the default is spread.

type.name: TaskSchedulingPolicy
type.doc: Specifies how tasks should be distributed across compute nodes.

properties.name: nodeFillType
properties.doc: How tasks should be distributed across compute nodes.

properties.name: userAccounts
properties.doc: The list of user accounts to be created on each node in the pool.

valueType.name: BatchUserAccount
valueType.doc: Properties used to create a user on an Azure Batch node.

properties.name: name
properties.doc: The name of the user account. Names can contain any Unicode characters up to a maximum length of 20.

properties.name: password
properties.doc: The password for the user account.

properties.name: elevationLevel
properties.summary: The elevation level of the user.
properties.doc: nonAdmin - The auto user is a standard user without elevated access. admin - The auto user is a user with elevated access and operates with full Administrator permissions. The default value is nonAdmin.

properties.name: linuxUserConfiguration
properties.summary: The Linux-specific user configuration for the user account.
properties.doc: This property is ignored if specified on a Windows pool. If not specified, the user is created with the default options.

type.name: BatchLinuxUserConfiguration
type.doc: Properties used to create a user account on a Linux node.

properties.name: uid
properties.summary: The user ID of the user account.
properties.doc: The uid and gid properties must be specified together or not at all. If not specified the underlying operating system picks the uid.

properties.name: gid
properties.summary: The group ID for the user account.
properties.doc: The uid and gid properties must be specified together or not at all. If not specified the underlying operating system picks the gid.

properties.name: sshPrivateKey
properties.summary: The SSH private key for the user account.
properties.doc: The private key must not be password protected. The private key is used to automatically configure asymmetric-key based authentication for SSH between nodes in a Linux pool when the pool's enableInterNodeCommunication property is true (it is ignored if enableInterNodeCommunication is false). It does this by placing the key pair into the user's .ssh directory. If not specified, password-less SSH is not configured between nodes (no modification of the user's .ssh directory is done).

properties.name: windowsUserConfiguration
properties.summary: The Windows-specific user configuration for the user account.
properties.doc: This property can only be specified if the user is on a Windows pool. If not specified and on a Windows pool, the user is created with the default options.

type.name: BatchWindowsUserConfiguration
type.doc: Properties used to create a user account on a Windows node.

properties.name: loginMode
properties.summary: Login mode for user
properties.doc: Specifies login mode for the user. The default value is Interactive.

properties.name: metadata
properties.summary: A list of name-value pairs associated with the pool as metadata.
properties.doc: The Batch service does not assign any meaning to metadata; it is solely for the use of user code.

valueType.name: BatchAccountPoolMetadataItem
valueType.doc: The Batch service does not assign any meaning to this metadata; it is solely for the use of user code.
valueType.summary: A name-value pair associated with a Batch service resource.

properties.name: name
properties.doc: The name of the metadata item.

properties.name: value
properties.doc: The value of the metadata item.

properties.name: startTask
properties.summary: A task specified to run on each compute node as it joins the pool.
properties.doc: In an PATCH (update) operation, this property can be set to an empty object to remove the start task from the pool.

type.name: BatchAccountPoolStartTask
type.doc: In some cases the start task may be re-run even though the node was not rebooted. Due to this, start tasks should be idempotent and exit gracefully if the setup they're performing has already been done. Special care should be taken to avoid start tasks which create breakaway process or install/launch services from the start task working directory, as this will block Batch from being able to re-run the start task.
type.summary: A task which is run when a compute node joins a pool in the Azure Batch service, or when the compute node is rebooted or reimaged.

properties.name: commandLine
properties.summary: The command line of the start task.
properties.doc: The command line does not run under a shell, and therefore cannot take advantage of shell features such as environment variable expansion. If you want to take advantage of such features, you should invoke the shell in the command line, for example using "cmd /c MyCommand" in Windows or "/bin/sh -c MyCommand" in Linux. Required if any other properties of the startTask are specified.

properties.name: resourceFiles
properties.doc: A list of files that the Batch service will download to the compute node before running the command line.

valueType.name: BatchResourceFile
valueType.doc: A single file or multiple files to be downloaded to a compute node.

properties.name: AutoBlobContainerName
properties.summary: The storage container name in the auto storage account.
properties.doc: The autoStorageContainerName, storageContainerUrl and httpUrl properties are mutually exclusive and one of them must be specified.

properties.name: BlobContainerUri
properties.summary: The URL of the blob container within Azure Blob Storage.
properties.doc: The autoStorageContainerName, storageContainerUrl and httpUrl properties are mutually exclusive and one of them must be specified. This URL must be readable and listable from compute nodes. There are three ways to get such a URL for a container in Azure storage: include a Shared Access Signature (SAS) granting read and list permissions on the container, use a managed identity with read and list permissions, or set the ACL for the container to allow public access.

properties.name: httpUrl
properties.summary: The URL of the file to download.
properties.doc: The autoStorageContainerName, storageContainerUrl and httpUrl properties are mutually exclusive and one of them must be specified. If the URL points to Azure Blob Storage, it must be readable from compute nodes. There are three ways to get such a URL for a blob in Azure storage: include a Shared Access Signature (SAS) granting read permissions on the blob, use a managed identity with read permission, or set the ACL for the blob or its container to allow public access.

properties.name: blobPrefix
properties.summary: The blob prefix to use when downloading blobs from an Azure Storage container. Only the blobs whose names begin with the specified prefix will be downloaded.
properties.doc: The property is valid only when autoStorageContainerName or storageContainerUrl is used. This prefix can be a partial filename or a subdirectory. If a prefix is not specified, all the files in the container will be downloaded.

properties.name: filePath
properties.summary: The location on the compute node to which to download the file, relative to the task's working directory.
properties.doc: If the httpUrl property is specified, the filePath is required and describes the path which the file will be downloaded to, including the filename. Otherwise, if the autoStorageContainerName or storageContainerUrl property is specified, filePath is optional and is the directory to download the files to. In the case where filePath is used as a directory, any directory structure already associated with the input data will be retained in full and appended to the specified filePath directory. The specified relative path cannot break out of the task's working directory (for example by using '..').

properties.name: fileMode
properties.summary: The file permission mode attribute in octal format.
properties.doc: This property applies only to files being downloaded to Linux compute nodes. It will be ignored if it is specified for a resourceFile which will be downloaded to a Windows node. If this property is not specified for a Linux node, then a default value of 0770 is applied to the file.

properties.name: Identity
properties.summary: The reference to the user assigned identity to use to access Azure Blob Storage specified by storageContainerUrl or httpUrl
properties.doc: The reference to a user assigned identity associated with the Batch pool which a compute node will use.

properties.name: environmentSettings
properties.doc: A list of environment variable settings for the start task.

valueType.name: BatchEnvironmentSetting
valueType.doc: An environment variable to be set on a task process.

properties.name: name
properties.doc: The name of the environment variable.

properties.name: value
properties.doc: The value of the environment variable.

properties.name: userIdentity
properties.summary: The user identity under which the start task runs.
properties.doc: If omitted, the task runs as a non-administrative user unique to the task.

type.name: BatchUserIdentity
type.doc: Specify either the userName or autoUser property, but not both.
type.summary: The definition of the user identity under which the task is run.

properties.name: userName
properties.summary: The name of the user identity under which the task is run.
properties.doc: The userName and autoUser properties are mutually exclusive; you must specify one but not both.

properties.name: autoUser
properties.summary: The auto user under which the task is run.
properties.doc: The userName and autoUser properties are mutually exclusive; you must specify one but not both.

type.name: BatchAutoUserSpecification
type.doc: Specifies the parameters for the auto user that runs a task on the Batch service.

properties.name: scope
properties.summary: The scope for the auto user
properties.doc: The default value is Pool. If the pool is running Windows a value of Task should be specified if stricter isolation between tasks is required. For example, if the task mutates the registry in a way which could impact other tasks, or if certificates have been specified on the pool which should not be accessible by normal tasks but should be accessible by start tasks.

properties.name: elevationLevel
properties.summary: The elevation level of the user.
properties.doc: The default value is nonAdmin.

properties.name: maxTaskRetryCount
properties.summary: The maximum number of times the task may be retried.
properties.doc: The Batch service retries a task if its exit code is nonzero. Note that this value specifically controls the number of retries. The Batch service will try the task once, and may then retry up to this limit. For example, if the maximum retry count is 3, Batch tries the task up to 4 times (one initial try and 3 retries). If the maximum retry count is 0, the Batch service does not retry the task. If the maximum retry count is -1, the Batch service retries the task without limit. Default is 0

properties.name: waitForSuccess
properties.summary: Whether the Batch service should wait for the start task to complete successfully (that is, to exit with exit code 0) before scheduling any tasks on the compute node.
properties.doc: If true and the start task fails on a compute node, the Batch service retries the start task up to its maximum retry count (maxTaskRetryCount). If the task has still not completed successfully after all retries, then the Batch service marks the compute node unusable, and will not schedule tasks to it. This condition can be detected via the node state and scheduling error detail. If false, the Batch service will not wait for the start task to complete. In this case, other tasks can start executing on the compute node while the start task is still running; and even if the start task fails, new tasks will continue to be scheduled on the node. The default is true.

properties.name: containerSettings
properties.summary: The settings for the container under which the start task runs.
properties.doc: When this is specified, all directories recursively below the AZ_BATCH_NODE_ROOT_DIR (the root of Azure Batch directories on the node) are mapped into the container, all task environment variables are mapped into the container, and the task command line is executed in the container.

type.name: BatchTaskContainerSettings
type.doc: The container settings for a task.

properties.name: containerRunOptions
properties.summary: Additional options to the container create command.
properties.doc: These additional options are supplied as arguments to the "docker create" command, in addition to those controlled by the Batch Service.

properties.name: imageName
properties.summary: The image to use to create the container in which the task will run.
properties.doc: This is the full image reference, as would be specified to "docker pull". If no tag is provided as part of the image name, the tag ":latest" is used as a default.

properties.name: registry
properties.summary: The private registry which contains the container image.
properties.doc: This setting can be omitted if was already provided at pool creation.

properties.name: workingDirectory
properties.doc: A flag to indicate where the container task working directory is. The default is 'taskWorkingDirectory'.

properties.name: containerHostBatchBindMounts
properties.summary: The paths you want to mounted to container task.
properties.doc: If this array is null or be not present, container task will mount entire temporary disk drive in windows (or AZ_BATCH_NODE_ROOT_DIR in Linux). It won't' mount any data paths into container if this array is set as empty.

valueType.name: ContainerHostBatchBindMountEntry
valueType.doc: The entry of path and mount mode you want to mount into task container.

properties.name: source
properties.doc: The paths which will be mounted to container task's container.

properties.name: isReadOnly
properties.summary: Mount this source path as read-only mode or not. Default value is false (read/write mode).
properties.doc: For Linux, if you mount this path as a read/write mode, this does not mean that all users in container have the read/write access for the path, it depends on the access in host VM. If this path is mounted read-only, all users within the container will not be able to modify the path.

properties.name: certificates
properties.summary: The list of certificates to be installed on each compute node in the pool.
properties.doc:
For Windows compute nodes, the Batch service installs the certificates to the specified certificate store and location. properties.name: mode
properties.doc:
Specifies the mode of an upgrade to virtual machines in the scale set.

Possible values are:

**Manual** - You control the application of updates to virtual machines in the scale set. You do this by using the manualUpgrade action.

**Automatic** - All virtual machines in the scale set are automatically updated at the same time.

**Rolling** - Scale set performs updates in batches with an optional pause time in between.

properties.doc:
Indicates whether OS upgrades should automatically be applied to scale set instances in a rolling fashion when a newer version of the OS image becomes available.

If this is set to true for Windows based pools, [WindowsConfiguration.enableAutomaticUpdates](https://learn.microsoft.com/rest/api/batchmanagement/pool/create?tabs=HTTP#windowsconfiguration) cannot be set to true.

properties.name: useRollingUpgradePolicy
properties.doc: Indicates whether rolling upgrade policy should be used during Auto OS Upgrade. Auto OS Upgrade will fallback to the default policy if no policy is defined on the VMSS.

properties.doc: The configuration parameters used while performing a rolling upgrade.

type.name: RollingUpgradePolicy
type.doc: The configuration parameters used while performing a rolling upgrade.

properties.name: enableCrossZoneUpgrade
properties.doc: Allow VMSS to ignore AZ boundaries when constructing upgrade batches. Take into consideration the Update Domain and maxBatchInstancePercent to determine the batch size. If this field is not set, Azure Azure Batch will not set its default value. The value of enableCrossZoneUpgrade on the created VirtualMachineScaleSet will be decided by the default configurations on VirtualMachineScaleSet. This field is able to be set to true or false only when using NodePlacementConfiguration as Zonal.

properties.name: maxBatchInstancePercent
properties.doc: The maximum percent of total virtual machine instances that will be upgraded simultaneously by the rolling upgrade in one batch. As this is a maximum, unhealthy instances in previous or future batches can cause the percentage of instances in a batch to decrease to ensure higher reliability. The value of this field should be between 5 and 100, inclusive. If both maxBatchInstancePercent and maxUnhealthyInstancePercent are assigned with value, the value of maxBatchInstancePercent should not be more than maxUnhealthyInstancePercent.

properties.name: maxUnhealthyInstancePercent
properties.doc: The maximum percentage of the total virtual machine instances in the scale set that can be simultaneously unhealthy, either as a result of being upgraded, or by being found in an unhealthy state by the virtual machine health checks before the rolling upgrade aborts. This constraint will be checked prior to starting any batch. The value of this field should be between 5 and 100, inclusive. If both maxBatchInstancePercent and maxUnhealthyInstancePercent are assigned with value, the value of maxBatchInstancePercent should not be more than maxUnhealthyInstancePercent.

properties.name: maxUnhealthyUpgradedInstancePercent
properties.doc: The maximum percentage of upgraded virtual machine instances that can be found to be in an unhealthy state. This check will happen after each batch is upgraded. If this percentage is ever exceeded, the rolling update aborts. The value of this field should be between 0 and 100, inclusive.

properties.name: pauseTimeBetweenBatches
properties.doc: The wait time between completing the update for all virtual machines in one batch and starting the next batch. The time duration should be specified in ISO 8601 format.

properties.name: prioritizeUnhealthyInstances
properties.doc: Upgrade all unhealthy instances in a scale set before any healthy instances.

properties.name: rollbackFailedInstancesOnPolicyBreach
properties.doc: Rollback failed instances to previous model if the Rolling Upgrade policy is violated.

If you try to delete a certificate that is being used by a pool or compute node, the status of the certificate changes to deleteFailed. If you intend to delete the certificate, you do not need to run this operation after the deletion failed. You must make sure that the certificate is not being used by any resources, and then you can try again to delete the certificate.
